==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mosquito
<hw>Mos*qui"to</hw> <pr>(m⟦ocr⟧s*k⟦emac⟧*t⟦osl⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Mosquitoes</plw>
<pr>(m⟦ocr⟧s*k⟦emac⟧*t⟦omac⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Sp.
<ets>mosquito</ets>, fr. <ets>mosca</ets>fly, L. <ets>musca</ets>. Cf.
<er>Musket</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of various
species of gnats of the genus <gen>Culex</gen> and allied genera. The
females have a proboscis containing, within the sheathlike labium, six
fine, sharp, needlelike organs with which they puncture the skin of man
and animals to suck the blood. These bites, when numerous, cause, in
many persons, considerable irritation and swelling, with some pain. The
larvae and pupae, called <stage>wigglers</stage>, are aquatic.</def>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>musquito</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Mosquito bar</b></col>, <col><b>Mosquito
net</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a net or curtain for excluding mosquitoes, --
used for beds and windows.</cd> -- <col><b>Mosquito fleet</b></col>,
<cd>a fleet of small vessels.</cd> -- <col><b>Mosquito hawk</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a dragon fly; -- so called because it captures
and feeds upon mosquitoes.</cd> -- <col><b>Mosquito netting</b></col>,
<cd>a loosely-woven gauzelike fabric for making mosquito
bars.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>mosquitofish</ent>⟦br⟧
